\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q2566598\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Joseph_Smith\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Joseph_Smith\"}, {\"begin\": 673, \"end\": 686, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canadian_Soccer_Association\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Canada Soccer\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canadian_Soccer_Association\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canadian_Soccer_Association\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Members\", \"from\": 518, \"to\": 525}, {\"ngram\": \"the drone\", \"from\": 558, \"to\": 567}, {\"ngram\": \"a staff member\", \"from\": 655, \"to\": 669}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The team was docked six points and the offending staff members suspended, with some Canadianscomplainingthat the treatment was unfair.\", \"from\": 688, \"to\": 822, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The team\", \"from\": 688, \"to\": 696}, {\"ngram\": \"the offending staff members\", \"from\": 723, \"to\": 750}, {\"ngram\": \"some Canadianscomplainingthat\", \"from\": 767, \"to\": 796}, {\"ngram\": \"the treatment\", \"from\": 797, \"to\": 810}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But the Canadian team got off lightly compared to those who were accused of cheating in the ancient Olympics.\", \"from\": 824, \"to\": 933, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 832, \"end\": 840, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canada\", \"score\": 0.9999839882856988, \"rank\": 1.601197013068739e-05, \"text\": \"Canadian\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canada\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Canada\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the ancient Olympics\", \"from\": 912, \"to\": 932}]}, {\"sentence\": \"\\\"At the games they give the runners who start too early a sound thrashing\\\" with a rod, says a Corinthian general inHerodotus' histories.\", \"from\": 934, \"to\": 1070, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1028, \"end\": 1038, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Corinth\", \"score\": 0.9999116920202258, \"rank\": 8.831577849610631e-05, \"text\": \"Corinthian\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Corinth\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ancient_Corinth\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the games\", \"from\": 938, \"to\": 947}, {\"ngram\": \"the runners\", \"from\": 958, \"to\": 969}, {\"ngram\": \"a rod\", \"from\": 1014, \"to\": 1019}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The worst cheaters would havenames carvedbeneath statues of Zeus near the Olympics venue, ensuring that they would live forever in infamy.\", \"from\": 1071, \"to\": 1209, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1131, \"end\": 1135, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zeus\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.2427389875312653e-38, \"text\": \"Zeus\", \"types\": [\"Q24229398\", \"Q178885\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zeus\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Zeus\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The worst cheaters\", \"from\": 1071, \"to\": 1089}, {\"ngram\": \"carvedbeneath statues\", \"from\": 1106, \"to\": 1127}, {\"ngram\": \"the Olympics venue\", \"from\": 1141, \"to\": 1159}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Cheating wasn't just a violation of the competitive spirit or a taint on their city's honor, but a transgression against the gods, for whom the games were held in thanksgiving.\", \"from\": 1210, \"to\": 1386, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Cheating\", \"from\": 1210, \"to\": 1218}, {\"ngram\": \"just a violation\", \"from\": 1226, \"to\": 1242}, {\"ngram\": \"the competitive spirit\", \"from\": 1246, \"to\": 1268}, {\"ngram\": \"a taint\", \"from\": 1272, \"to\": 1279}, {\"ngram\": \"their city's honor\", \"from\": 1283, \"to\": 1301}, {\"ngram\": \"a transgression\", \"from\": 1307, \"to\": 1322}, {\"ngram\": \"the gods\", \"from\": 1331, \"to\": 1339}, {\"ngram\": \"the games\", \"from\": 1350, \"to\": 1359}, {\"ngram\": \"thanksgiving\", \"from\": 1373, \"to\": 1385}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Related Some Greeks took the precaution of putting the fate of disfavored athletes in the hands of divine intervention, then, by inscribing curses in a strip of lead and then hiding it somewhere in the athletic facilities.\", \"from\": 1388, \"to\": 1611, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Some Greeks\", \"from\": 1396, \"to\": 1407}, {\"ngram\": \"the precaution\", \"from\": 1413, \"to\": 1427}, {\"ngram\": \"the fate\", \"from\": 1439, \"to\": 1447}, {\"ngram\": \"disfavored athletes\", \"from\": 1451, \"to\": 1470}, {\"ngram\": \"the hands\", \"from\": 1474, \"to\": 1483}, {\"ngram\": \"divine intervention\", \"from\": 1487, \"to\": 1506}, {\"ngram\": \"curses\", \"from\": 1528, \"to\": 1534}, {\"ngram\": \"a strip\", \"from\": 1538, \"to\": 1545}, {\"ngram\": \"lead\", \"from\": 1549, \"to\": 1553}, {\"ngram\": \"the athletic facilities\", \"from\": 1586, \"to\": 1609}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Others used more direct means to gain an advantage, even when the rules were simple and permissive; onecup from 490 BCdepicts a wrestler breaking the only two prohibitions in that sport by biting his opponent and attempting to gouge out his eyes.\", \"from\": 1612, \"to\": 1858, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Others\", \"from\": 1612, \"to\": 1618}, {\"ngram\": \"more direct means\", \"from\": 1624, \"to\": 1641}, {\"ngram\": \"an advantage\", \"from\": 1650, \"to\": 1662}, {\"ngram\": \"the rules\", \"from\": 1674, \"to\": 1683}, {\"ngram\": \"onecup\", \"from\": 1712, \"to\": 1718}, {\"ngram\": \"490 BCdepicts\", \"from\": 1724, \"to\": 1737}, {\"ngram\": \"the only two prohibitions\", \"from\": 1758, \"to\": 1783}, {\"ngram\": \"that sport\", \"from\": 1787, \"to\": 1797}, {\"ngram\": \"his opponent\", \"from\": 1808, \"to\": 1820}, {\"ngram\": \"his eyes\", \"from\": 1849, \"to\": 1857}]}, {\"sentence\": \"An official stands at the periphery, preparing to strike the offender with his rod.\", \"from\": 1859, \"to\": 1942, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"An official\", \"from\": 1859, \"to\": 1870}, {\"ngram\": \"the periphery\", \"from\": 1881, \"to\": 1894}, {\"ngram\": \"the offender\", \"from\": 1916, \"to\": 1928}, {\"ngram\": \"his rod\", \"from\": 1934, \"to\": 1941}]}, {\"sentence\": \"City-states, hoping to win civic glory, sometimes schemed to bribe top athletes to falsely claim that city as their own.\", \"from\": 1944, \"to\": 2064, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"City-states\", \"from\": 1944, \"to\": 1955}, {\"ngram\": \"civic glory\", \"from\": 1971, \"to\": 1982}, {\"ngram\": \"top athletes\", \"from\": 2011, \"to\": 2023}, {\"ngram\": \"that city\", \"from\": 2041, \"to\": 2050}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Whenone of those athletesran for Syracuse instead of his home city of Croton, the government tore down his statue and confiscated his house, converting it into a public jail.\", \"from\": 2065, \"to\": 2239, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2098, \"end\": 2106, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Syracuse_Orange_football\", \"score\": 0.673608000277621, \"rank\": 0.28260256792232774, \"text\": \"Syracuse\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Syracuse_Orange_football\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Syracuse_Orange_football\"}, {\"begin\": 2135, \"end\": 2141, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crotone\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.9275678284704596e-25, \"text\": \"Croton\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crotone\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Crotone\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"those athletesran\", \"from\": 2076, \"to\": 2093}, {\"ngram\": \"the government\", \"from\": 2143, \"to\": 2157}, {\"ngram\": \"his statue\", \"from\": 2168, \"to\": 2178}, {\"ngram\": \"his house\", \"from\": 2195, \"to\": 2204}, {\"ngram\": \"a public jail\", \"from\": 2225, \"to\": 2238}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The Roman emperor Nero, who fancied himself a man for all seasons (or wanted to convince everyone else he was), participated in the 67 AD Olympics and won every single contest in which he was a competitor.\", \"from\": 2241, \"to\": 2446, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2245, \"end\": 2250, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\", \"score\": 0.8404099515002722, \"rank\": 0.18977140491942354, \"text\": \"Roman\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\"}, {\"begin\": 2259, \"end\": 2263, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.3213137144742493e-33, \"text\": \"Nero\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"a man\", \"from\": 2285, \"to\": 2290}, {\"ngram\": \"all seasons\", \"from\": 2295, \"to\": 2306}, {\"ngram\": \"everyone\", \"from\": 2330, \"to\": 2338}, {\"ngram\": \"the 67 AD Olympics\", \"from\": 2369, \"to\": 2387}, {\"ngram\": \"every single contest\", \"from\": 2396, \"to\": 2416}, {\"ngram\": \"a competitor\", \"from\": 2433, \"to\": 2445}]}, {\"sentence\": \"During the 10-horse chariot race, he was thrown off his vehicle and had to leave the track to avoid being trampled, but he pressured the judges crown him anyway; Nero would have won the race if he was able to complete it, of course.\", \"from\": 2447, \"to\": 2679, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2609, \"end\": 2613, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.3213137144742493e-33, \"text\": \"Nero\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nero\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the 10-horse chariot race\", \"from\": 2454, \"to\": 2479}, {\"ngram\": \"his vehicle\", \"from\": 2499, \"to\": 2510}, {\"ngram\": \"the track\", \"from\": 2528, \"to\": 2537}, {\"ngram\": \"the judges\", \"from\": 2580, \"to\": 2590}, {\"ngram\": \"the race\", \"from\": 2629, \"to\": 2637}, {\"ngram\": \"course\", \"from\": 2672, \"to\": 2678}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the Olympics and other ancient sporting events, organizers got in on the act as well,pocketing bribesto rig the proceedings if they thought they could get away with it.\", \"from\": 2681, \"to\": 2852, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the Olympics\", \"from\": 2684, \"to\": 2696}, {\"ngram\": \"other ancient sporting events\", \"from\": 2701, \"to\": 2730}, {\"ngram\": \"organizers\", \"from\": 2732, \"to\": 2742}, {\"ngram\": \"the act\", \"from\": 2753, \"to\": 2760}, {\"ngram\": \"bribesto rig\", \"from\": 2779, \"to\": 2791}, {\"ngram\": \"the proceedings\", \"from\": 2792, \"to\": 2807}]}, {\"sentence\": \"For some people, spite was its own reward; the historianProcopius recordsthat when the Persian king Khosrow I captured the Roman city of Apamea in 540 AD, he arranged a chariot race in which hippodrome attendants, following his orders, held up the charioteer from the Roman emperor'sfavored Blue factionso that his rival Green competitor would pass him and win.\", \"from\": 2853, \"to\": 3214, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2953, \"end\": 2962, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Khosrow_I\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Khosrow I\", \"types\": [\"Q729\", \"Q5\", \"Q215627\", \"Q19088\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Khosrow_I\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Khosrow_I\"}, {\"begin\": 2976, \"end\": 2981, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\", \"score\": 0.8404099515002722, \"rank\": 0.18977140491942354, \"text\": \"Roman\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\"}, {\"begin\": 2990, \"end\": 2996, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Qalaat_al-Madiq\", \"score\": 0.9402011246558685, \"rank\": 0.06360221635093709, \"text\": \"Apamea\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\", \"Q3957\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Qalaat_al-Madiq\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Qalaat_al-Madiq\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"some people\", \"from\": 2857, \"to\": 2868}, {\"ngram\": \"spite\", \"from\": 2870, \"to\": 2875}, {\"ngram\": \"its own reward\", \"from\": 2880, \"to\": 2894}, {\"ngram\": \"the historianProcopius recordsthat\", \"from\": 2896, \"to\": 2930}, {\"ngram\": \"540 AD\", \"from\": 3000, \"to\": 3006}, {\"ngram\": \"a chariot race\", \"from\": 3020, \"to\": 3034}, {\"ngram\": \"hippodrome attendants\", \"from\": 3044, \"to\": 3065}, {\"ngram\": \"his orders\", \"from\": 3077, \"to\": 3087}, {\"ngram\": \"the charioteer\", \"from\": 3097, \"to\": 3111}, {\"ngram\": \"the Roman emperor'sfavored Blue factionso\", \"from\": 3117, \"to\": 3158}, {\"ngram\": \"his rival Green competitor\", \"from\": 3164, \"to\": 3190}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The Olympics and chariot racing declined as the Roman world fragmented, and knightly tournaments, which served to entertain and prepare its participants for war, emerged as the new popular spectacle.\", \"from\": 3216, \"to\": 3415, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3264, \"end\": 3269, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\", \"score\": 0.8404099515002722, \"rank\": 0.18977140491942354, \"text\": \"Roman\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Roman_Republic\"}], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"The Olympics\", \"from\": 3216, \"to\": 3228}, {\"ngram\": \"chariot racing\", \"from\": 3233, \"to\": 3247}, {\"ngram\": \"knightly tournaments\", \"from\": 3292, \"to\": 3312}, {\"ngram\": \"its participants\", \"from\": 3352, \"to\": 3368}, {\"ngram\": \"war\", \"from\": 3373, \"to\": 3376}, {\"ngram\": \"the new popular spectacle\", \"from\": 3389, \"to\": 3414}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Tournaments began as rougher, less \\\"gentlemanly\\\" affairs in which competitors rode against each other with lances and then proceeded to fight with close-quarters weapons ahorse or on foot.\", \"from\": 3416, \"to\": 3604, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Tournaments\", \"from\": 3416, \"to\": 3427}, {\"ngram\": \"less \\\"gentlemanly\\\" affairs\", \"from\": 3446, \"to\": 3472}, {\"ngram\": \"competitors\", \"from\": 3482, \"to\": 3493}, {\"ngram\": \"lances\", \"from\": 3523, \"to\": 3529}, {\"ngram\": \"close-quarters weapons\", \"from\": 3563, \"to\": 3585}, {\"ngram\": \"foot\", \"from\": 3599, \"to\": 3603}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Prizes were not given to the participants by the hosts, but taken from rival competitors after they were incapacitated in the form of his arms, armor or prized destrier; in many cases, a competitor himself was taken captive and ransomed for a hefty sum.\", \"from\": 3605, \"to\": 3858, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Prizes\", \"from\": 3605, \"to\": 3611}, {\"ngram\": \"the participants\", \"from\": 3630, \"to\": 3646}, {\"ngram\": \"the hosts\", \"from\": 3650, \"to\": 3659}, {\"ngram\": \"rival competitors\", \"from\": 3676, \"to\": 3693}, {\"ngram\": \"the form\", \"from\": 3727, \"to\": 3735}, {\"ngram\": \"his arms\", \"from\": 3739, \"to\": 3747}, {\"ngram\": \"armor\", \"from\": 3749, \"to\": 3754}, {\"ngram\": \"prized destrier\", \"from\": 3758, \"to\": 3773}, {\"ngram\": \"many cases\", \"from\": 3778, \"to\": 3788}, {\"ngram\": \"a competitor\", \"from\": 3790, \"to\": 3802}, {\"ngram\": \"a hefty sum\", \"from\": 3846, \"to\": 3857}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the chaotic tangle of dust, horseflesh and steel, finding an unexpected advantage was not difficult for those unyoked from scruple.Count Philip of Flanderswould often arrive at the lists with his retinue and publicly declare his intention to spectate rather than fight.\", \"from\": 3860, \"to\": 4132, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the chaotic tangle\", \"from\": 3863, \"to\": 3881}, {\"ngram\": \"dust\", \"from\": 3885, \"to\": 3889}, {\"ngram\": \"horseflesh\", \"from\": 3891, \"to\": 3901}, {\"ngram\": \"steel\", \"from\": 3906, \"to\": 3911}, {\"ngram\": \"an unexpected advantage\", \"from\": 3921, \"to\": 3944}, {\"ngram\": \"scruple\", \"from\": 3986, \"to\": 3993}, {\"ngram\": \"Count Philip\", \"from\": 3994, \"to\": 4006}, {\"ngram\": \"the lists\", \"from\": 4040, \"to\": 4049}, {\"ngram\": \"his retinue\", \"from\": 4055, \"to\": 4066}, {\"ngram\": \"his intention\", \"from\": 4088, \"to\": 4101}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Only after the ensuing m\\u00eal\\u00e9e had left his potential opponents \\\"weary, disarrayed and disorganised\\\" would Philip then sweep in with his knights and subdue the easy pickings.\", \"from\": 4133, \"to\": 4305, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the ensuing m\\u00eal\\u00e9e\", \"from\": 4144, \"to\": 4161}, {\"ngram\": \"his potential opponents\", \"from\": 4171, \"to\": 4194}, {\"ngram\": \"Philip\", \"from\": 4238, \"to\": 4244}, {\"ngram\": \"his knights\", \"from\": 4264, \"to\": 4275}, {\"ngram\": \"the easy pickings\", \"from\": 4287, \"to\": 4304}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Inasmuch as this resembled the use of a reserve force in battle in an activity meant to emulate battle (though Philip was not coming to the aid of anyone, like a reserve typically does), the knights and judges accepted the use of this tactic.\", \"from\": 4307, \"to\": 4549, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"the use\", \"from\": 4334, \"to\": 4341}, {\"ngram\": \"a reserve force\", \"from\": 4345, \"to\": 4360}, {\"ngram\": \"battle\", \"from\": 4364, \"to\": 4370}, {\"ngram\": \"an activity\", \"from\": 4374, \"to\": 4385}, {\"ngram\": \"battle\", \"from\": 4403, \"to\": 4409}, {\"ngram\": \"Philip\", \"from\": 4418, \"to\": 4424}, {\"ngram\": \"the aid\", \"from\": 4443, \"to\": 4450}, {\"ngram\": \"anyone\", \"from\": 4454, \"to\": 4460}, {\"ngram\": \"a reserve\", \"from\": 4467, \"to\": 4476}, {\"ngram\": \"the knights\", \"from\": 4494, \"to\": 4505}, {\"ngram\": \"judges\", \"from\": 4510, \"to\": 4516}, {\"ngram\": \"the use\", \"from\": 4526, \"to\": 4533}, {\"ngram\": \"this tactic\", \"from\": 4537, \"to\": 4548}]}, {\"sentence\": \"As casualties mounted in the traditional m\\u00eal\\u00e9e and church officials expressed disapproval at the carnage, tournaments slowly became safer, more ritualized affairs, and jousting between two knights evolved from warm-up activity to main event, swapping roles with a tamer (and therefore more boring) version of the m\\u00eal\\u00e9e.\", \"from\": 4550, \"to\": 4869, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"casualties\", \"from\": 4553, \"to\": 4563}, {\"ngram\": \"the traditional m\\u00eal\\u00e9e\", \"from\": 4575, \"to\": 4596}, {\"ngram\": \"church officials\", \"from\": 4601, \"to\": 4617}, {\"ngram\": \"disapproval\", \"from\": 4628, \"to\": 4639}, {\"ngram\": \"the carnage\", \"from\": 4643, \"to\": 4654}, {\"ngram\": \"tournaments\", \"from\": 4656, \"to\": 4667}, {\"ngram\": \"safer, more ritualized affairs\", \"from\": 4682, \"to\": 4712}, {\"ngram\": \"two knights\", \"from\": 4735, \"to\": 4746}, {\"ngram\": \"warm-up activity\", \"from\": 4760, \"to\": 4776}, {\"ngram\": \"main event\", \"from\": 4780, \"to\": 4790}, {\"ngram\": \"roles\", \"from\": 4801, \"to\": 4806}, {\"ngram\": \"therefore more boring) version\", \"from\": 4825, \"to\": 4855}, {\"ngram\": \"the m\\u00eal\\u00e9e\", \"from\": 4859, \"to\": 4868}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Organizers publishedrulebooksthat regulated everything from the actual combat (no aiming at unprotected parts!)\", \"from\": 4870, \"to\": 4981, \"entities\": [], \"noun_phrases\": [{\"ngram\": \"Organizers\", \"from\": 4870, \"to\": 4880}, {\"ngram\": \"publishedrulebooksthat\", \"from\": 4881, \"to\": 4903}, {\"ngram\": \"everything\", \"from\": 4914, \"to\": 4924}, {\"n